reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:72:      "overlap": "Gives a close Advaita account of witness-consciousness as the abiding dimension in which changing experiences appear, directly overlapping the hidden-seer custody leg.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:84:      "overlap": "Shows apophatic language turning back on its own propositions and names across Greek, Christian, and Islamic texts, close to the Christian unknowing side.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:94:  "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.72 to about 0.58. The custody phrase appears fresh, but the structure sits close to established work on pure consciousness, constructivism, theistic versus monistic typologies, witness-consciousness, and apophasis.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:98:    "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners independently identify a decisive handoff point and report that no-owner, witness, and God-directed instructions change practice understanding.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:117:    "risk_of_overread": "High. The term attention imports modern psychology into texts that speak about clinging, Self, inner ruler, will, love, and God. Bahiya may be about ending clinging rather than leaving attention unowned. Brihadaranyaka may be ontological rather than attentional. The Cloud may intensify desire rather than suspend ownership.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:118:    "secondary_literature_gap": "I did not find the exact phrase or structure of attention custody across Buddhist no-self, Advaita witness, and Christian apophatic prayer. However, close prior work already distinguishes common mystical experience, culturally shaped interpretation, monistic versus theistic typologies, witness-consciousness, and pure awareness. The originality is therefore a reframing of a known comparison around practice-level ownership language, not a standalone discovery.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:119:    "structural_observation": "The primary contrast is real but narrower than the proposed model. Udana 1.10 uses the same seeing, hearing, sensing, cognizing sequence and then removes locatable self-reference. Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 uses seeing, hearing, perceiving, knowing to identify the sole inner ruler and Self. This supports a strong no-owner versus hidden-seer contrast. The Christian leg is less exact: The Cloud of Unknowing chapter 3 begins with love and intent toward God, rather than first freeing neutral attention and then assigning it. Pseudo-Dionysius further strains the model because Mystical Theology chapter 5 places the Cause beyond both affirmation and negation, so even God as a stable recipient is apophatically unstable. Cloud source: https://sacred-texts.com/chr/cou/cou08.htm. Dionysius source: https://hekhal.org/texts/mystical-theology-dionysius/"
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json:131:  "unlike_statement": "Unlike common-core or constructivist accounts, this idea says the decisive variable is not only whether an experience is the same or differently interpreted, but whether training assigns loosened attention to no owner, the witnessing Self, or God."
