reviews/originality/2026-05-30-were-you-absent-or-were-you-aware-dda63bef681b717d.json:123:      "Theravada teachers familiar with cessation and not-self practice",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-were-you-absent-or-were-you-aware-dda63bef681b717d.json:137:    "structural_observation": "Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23 protects an unlost seer when no second object appears, which is not simply a remembered in-gap experience. It is closer to a doctrinal and inferential witness claim. MN 44 describes cessation through prior training and emergence, not through a private self-report of awareness inside the gap. AN 9.34 treats cessation as known through discernment and fruit. SN 22.59 blocks turning consciousness into owner. A three-way codebook, inferred-from-absence, claimed-in-gap awareness, and verified-by-training or fruit, fits the sources better than the candidate's two-way fork."
reviews/originality/2026-05-29-not-every-practice-is-a-tool-6243c8e923d5f36f.md:71:- If: The separable-result question is a real scope gate. Then: Texts and manuals coded as non-instrumental from doctrinal passages will show less result-custody language and more conduct, form, vow, teacher, or community correction language in held-out sources. Weakens if: Self-described non-instrumental traditions contain result-custody language as centrally as instrumental traditions, or coders cannot distinguish result refusal from result relocation. Test surface: Split-source coding of Dogen, Shinran, MN 22, koan curricula, Advaita inquiry, apophatic Christian sources, Sufi fana and baqa, and ritual manuals.
