reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.json:12:    "SN 22.59 can be read as requiring any proposed remainder to undergo the same not-self test.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.json:23:  "exact_claim": "The decisive difference between Upanishadic witness language and early Buddhist not-self may be an inference policy after negation: whether non-objectifiability shifts the burden toward an unobjectifiable seer or keeps the burden against any self-claim.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.json:27:      "expected_observation": "Advaita commentaries should use non-objectifiability to block denial of Self, while Buddhist commentaries should apply impermanence, conditionality, or not-self analysis to any proposed witness-like remainder.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.json:33:      "expected_observation": "They report that one instruction says recognize the unobjectifiable, while another says investigate the recognizer or do not appropriate it.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.json:42:    "Advaita self-luminosity consciousness not inferred pramana witness",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.json:45:    "Buddhist not-self strategy burden of proof self claim",
